<Base title="OSfile (.primefile) — ostk governance" description="The kernel identity document. Written by the OS, not by you. Records the running kernel version and signing authority.">
  <div class="container">
    <h1>OSfile <span style="font-weight: normal; color: var(--color-muted)">(.primefile)</span></h1>
    <p class="lead">The kernel's identity document. The OS writes it. You read it to verify what's running.</p>

    <h2>What it is</h2>
    <p>
      The OSfile is the signed <code>.primefile</code> — the kernel identity document.
      The OS's equivalent of your HUMANFILE. You don't write it. The kernel writes and
      signs it at initialization, and updates it on version changes.
    </p>
    <p>
      Read it to understand what kernel version is running, who signed it, and
      what the active trust chain looks like.
    </p>

    <h2>OSfile vs ostk.toml</h2>
    <p>These are two different things:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>OSfile (.primefile)</strong> — the kernel's signed identity document. Written and owned by the OS. Records version, signing keys, session state. You verify it; you don't edit it.</li>
      <li><strong>ostk.toml</strong> — project collaboration config. Defines project-level settings for agent coordination: default kernel version, laws, pin defaults, feature flags. You write and maintain this.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>The OSfile proves what kernel is running. <code>ostk.toml</code> configures how your team uses it.</p>

    <h2>Location</h2>
    <p><code>.ostk/.primefile</code> — the signed kernel identity, in your project's ostk state directory.</p>
    <p><code>ostk.toml</code> — project collaboration config, at your repository root.</p>

    <h2>Example</h2>
    <pre><code>---BEGIN HAYSTACK.PRIME KERNEL DECLARATION---

KERNEL: @haystack.prime
VERSION: 2.0.0
CREATED: 2026-03-10T00:00:00Z
ROTATED: 2026-03-19T00:00:00Z

AUTHORITY:
  Primary: @scott (Human operator, HUMANFILE authority)
  Kernel: @haystack.prime (Persistent kernel, GOVERNANCE.md authority)
  Co-signers: Both keys required for mutation

KEYS:
  T0 Human Root:
    Name: Scott Meyer &lt;scott@ostk.ai&gt;
    Key: BAF08C963C7E3184
    Algorithm: ed25519

  T1 Kernel:
    Name: @haystack.prime (v2.0) &lt;kernel@haystack.prime&gt;
    Key: 907A200DA6C869EB
    Algorithm: ed25519

  T1 CI:
    Name: @haystack.prime.ci &lt;ci@haystack.prime&gt;
    Key: C78631AA6893C46C
    Algorithm: ed25519
    Cross-signed by: 907A200DA6C869EB

LINEAGE:
  Root: @scott GPG signature
  Co-sign: @haystack.prime GPG signature
  Chain: Unbroken from 2026-03-10

---SIGNATURES BELOW---</code></pre>

    <h2>ostk.toml example</h2>
    <p>Created by <code>ostk init</code> at your project root:</p>
    <pre><code># ostk.toml — my-project

[project]
name = "my-project"

[kernel]
version = ">=2.2.2"
boot_mode = "embedded-first"
laws = ["invisible-write", "ephemeral", "filesystem", "OCC", "invisible-infra"]

[pins.default]
read = [".ostk/", ".language"]
write = [".ostk/store/default/"]
execute = "shell(readonly)"
deny = ["write-kernel", "modify-governance"]

[features]
tui = true
agents = true
audit = true</code></pre>

    <h2>Fields</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Field</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>KERNEL</code></td><td>Kernel identity name. Default: <code>@haystack.prime</code>.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>VERSION</code></td><td>Kernel declaration version. Compare to latest release to check for updates.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>AUTHORITY</code></td><td>Who controls the kernel — primary (human), kernel, and co-signer requirements.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>KEYS</code></td><td>GPG key registry: T0 human root, T1 kernel, T1 CI. Algorithm and cross-signature info.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>LINEAGE</code></td><td>Root of trust chain, co-signers, and chain continuity date.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>GOVERNANCE</code></td><td>References to ENTITYFILE, GOVERNANCE.md, MANIFESTO.md, and catastrophic loss procedure.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>Signature verification</h2>
    <p>
      The <code>.primefile</code> is GPG-signed by the kernel root key. To verify the
      running kernel hasn't been tampered with:
    </p>
    <pre><code>gpg --verify .ostk/.primefile.asc .ostk/.primefile</code></pre>
    <p>
      If verification fails, the kernel should not be trusted. The signature chain runs:
      human T0 key → kernel root key → CI key. Each link in the chain is cross-signed.
    </p>

    <h2>You don't edit this</h2>
    <p>
      Unlike HUMANFILE and ENTITYFILE, you do not write the OSfile. The kernel owns it.
      Modifying it manually will invalidate the signature and may cause the kernel to
      refuse to boot. If you need to update kernel configuration, use the provided
      governance commands rather than direct edits.
    </p>

